stars.name: Sun
stars.desc: The Star of the Solar System
stars.paragraph: The Sun is the center of the Solar System. It is a middle-sized yellow main-sequence star, which is currently fusing hydrogen into helium in its core. It is composed of plasma and incandescent gas at unimaginably hot temperatures. The Sun’s emission of light from its surface is necessary for the existence of life on Earth, allowing for the process of photosynthesis, and driving weather and climate patterns, as well as bringing light and heat to all of the planets and moons of the Solar System. The Sun has been influential to cultures throughout human history, being regarded as a deity, and celebrated around the world. In about five billion years, the Sun will run out of hydrogen fuel and swell into a red giant, before finally becoming a white dwarf where it will gradually cool for all eternity.

stars.name: Alpha Centauri A
stars.systemParagraph: Alpha Centauri is the closest star system to Earth at just 4 light years away, in the constellation Centaurus. It is a triple star system composed of three stars.
stars.paragraph: Alpha Centauri A is a sun-like star in a binary orbit with Alpha Centauri B.

stars.name: Alpha Centauri B
stars.paragraph: Alpha Centauri B is a sun-like star in a binary orbit with Alpha Centauri A.

stars.name: Proxima Centauri
stars.paragraph: Proxima Centauri is a small red dwarf star in the Alpha Centauri system. It orbits Alpha Centauri A and B. Proxima contains two known planets that orbit it.

stars.name: Sirius A
stars.systemParagraph: Sirius is the brightest star in the night sky. It is a binary star system made of a massive blue star and a small white dwarf. The star is also known as the “Dog Star.”
stars.paragraph: Sirius A is a large blue star much larger than the Sun. It is much brighter than Sirius B which makes it dominate the star system.

stars.name: Sirius B

stars.name: Betelgeuse
stars.systemParagraph: Betelgeuse is a behemoth red supergiant in the constellation Orion. It is one of the most well-known stars. In the infrared, Betelgeuse appears as the brightest star in the sky, despite being hundreds of light years away. It is a runaway star with no known companions. It is due to explode in a supernova at some point in the next 100,000 years, although we won’t know exactly when until it happens.

stars.name: Polaris Aa
stars.systemParagraph: Polaris is the North Star, the closest star to the celestial north pole. It appears motionless in the sky due to its position, providing a baseline for measurement and astrometry. For centuries Polaris has helped civilizations with navigation and been a part of their cultures. Due to the Earth’s axial precession (or “wobble”), the star will eventually lose its status as the North Star in a few millennia. Polaris is actually a triple star system.
stars.paragraph: Polaris Aa is a massive supergiant star in a binary system with the Ab star. Aa dominates the Polaris system and provides the light we see as the North Star.

stars.name: UY Scuti
stars.systemParagraph: UY Scuti is an absolutely enormous star in the constellation Scutum; it is one of the largest stars known to man. The absolute monster is over 1700 times the size of the Sun, although only around 30 times its mass. UY Scuti dwarfs the Sun, making it look like a penny compared to a football field. If UY Scuti was placed where our Sun is now, all of the planets up to Jupiter would be completely swallowed by it.

planets.name: Mercury
planets.paragraph: Mercury is the 1st planet from the Sun, and it is the smallest planet in the Solar System. It travels around the sun very quickly, and this causes its day length to actually be longer than its year. Its surface is heavily cratered and it lacks an atmosphere, similar to our Moon. This causes its temperatures to range from very hot on the side facing the Sun to very cold on the dark side.

planets.name: Venus
planets.paragraph: Venus is the 2nd planet from the Sun, and it is the hottest and most hellish planet in the Solar System. It is considered Earth’s sister planet, although its extremely hot and dense atmosphere means we would not be able to survive even with protective equipment. Venus also rotates in the opposite direction from the other inner planets, and it does so very slowly; it completes an entire orbit of the Sun before completing one full rotation.
planets.nameReason: it was considered the brightest and most beautiful planet

planets.name: Earth
planets.paragraph: Earth is the 3rd planet from the Sun, and it is the only known planet to contain life.  It is a terrestrial planet with an active and habitable surface, unique among its neighbors in the Solar System. Its position in the Solar System enables water to exist as a liquid, which makes up almost three-quarters of its surface. The atmosphere is also an integral part of the planet, made of mostly nitrogen and oxygen, which helps stop harmful radiation and meteors from impacting the surface. These factors make Earth perfectly suitable for the development of life; it is the only habitable planet in the Solar System. Earth formed around 4.5 billion years ago, and early primordial life is believed to have emerged within the first billion years of the planet’s existence. Evolution has led to great biodiversity across Earth, a result of the variety of landforms and environments across the globe that different forms of life have adapted to. On the inside, Earth’s geology is divided into four layers: the crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core. Tectonic plates and internal geologic activity cause varied topology and environments to exist on the surface.

planets.name: Mars
planets.paragraph: Mars is the 4th planet from the Sun, and it is the most likely planet for future space travel. At one time, Mars likely was hospitable for life and had liquid water, but slowly it has evolved into a desolate landscape of rusting iron, which gives it its distinctive red color. It also contains the largest mountain in the Solar System, Olympus Mons.

planets.name: Jupiter
planets.paragraph: Jupiter is the 5th planet from the Sun, and it is the largest planet in the Solar System. It is a gas giant and lacks a solid surface. Its distinctive Great Red Spot is a storm that has been active for hundreds of years. Its magnetic field is very strong, and it has four large moons, as well as many other smaller ones.
planets.namesake: Roman king of the gods, god of thunder
planets.nameReason: it was the largest planet and seen as the most powerful

planets.name: Saturn
planets.paragraph: Saturn is the 6th planet from the Sun, and it has the largest and most prominent ring system in the Solar System. Its distinctive rings are composed of ice, rocks, and dust particles in orbit around the planet; they likely formed from debris resulting from the destruction of a former moon. The planet itself is the second largest in the Solar System. Like the other gas giants, Saturn has no solid surface. It also has the most known moons of any planet (82).
planets.namesake: Roman god of generation, wealth, agriculture, and time

planets.name: Uranus
planets.paragraph: Uranus is the 7th planet from the Sun, and it has the most unique rotation in the Solar System. Most likely the result of a large collision, the planet rotates on its side, and experiences extreme seasons that last for two decades at a time. It is considered an ice giant; it is composed of the coldest atmosphere in the solar system, containing icy ammonia and methane.

planets.name: Neptune
planets.paragraph: Neptune is the 8th planet from the Sun, and it is the only planet in the Solar System that was predicted before being discovered. Like Uranus, it is an ice giant, composed of ices in its cold atmosphere. Its atmosphere is very active and has strong weather patterns, including the highest wind speeds ever recorded in the Solar System.
planets.discoveredBy: Johann Galle and Urbain Le Verrier
planets.nameReason: it appears blue, resembling the sea

planets.name: Pluto
planets.desc: Dwarf Planet in the Kuiper Belt
planets.paragraph: Pluto is a large dwarf planet beyond the orbit of Neptune. It has a very elliptical orbit, and it was once considered the 9th planet. It is sometimes considered to be in a binary system with its large moon, Charon, as the objects are influenced by each other greatly.

planets.name: Ceres
planets.desc: Dwarf Planet in the Asteroid Belt
planets.paragraph: Ceres is the largest known asteroid in the Asteroid Belt, and it is also considered a dwarf planet. It alone makes up over a third of the mass of the Asteroid Belt.

planets.name: Eris
planets.desc: Dwarf Planet in the Kuiper Belt
planets.paragraph: Eris is a large dwarf planet in the Kuiper Belt with a very elliptical orbit, making it by far the farthest dwarf planet from the sun near its aphelion.
planets.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
planets.namesake: Greek goddess of chaos, daughter of Zeus

planets.name: Haumea
planets.desc: Dwarf Planet in the Kuiper Belt
planets.paragraph: Haumea is a small dwarf planet in the Kuiper Belt. The planet’s rotation is so fast that it causes it to be shaped like an egg.
planets.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
planets.namesake: Hawaiian goddess of fertility and childbirth

planets.name: Makemake
planets.desc: Dwarf Planet in the Kuiper Belt
planets.paragraph: Makemake is a dwarf planet in the Kuiper Belt. It was the last dwarf planet to be discovered due to its high inclination orbit, even though it is one of the brightest.
planets.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
planets.namesake: creator of humanity in the Rapa Nui mythology of Easter Island

planets.name: Planet Nine
planets.desc: Hypothetical Planet in the Outer Solar System
planets.paragraph: Planet Nine (or Planet X) is a hypothetical planet that is believed to exist in the outer Solar System. It is hypothesized due to gravitational clustering patterns of trans-Neptunian objects, and it likely orbits the Sun several hundreds of AU away; it would likely take tens of thousands of years for the planet to orbit the Sun once. No observation of Planet Nine has ever taken place; if it did exist, it would be difficult due to the immense distance between it and Earth. It was likely formed closer to the Sun and ejected from the Solar System long ago.

moons.name: Moon
moons.paragraph: Earth's moon is its sole natural satellite; it is often called Luna. The Moon is notable for its distinctive lunar phases as viewed from Earth as it orbits, as well as its influence on cultures, mythologies, and timekeeping throughout human history. It is also the cause for tidal forces on Earth; it is tidally locked, so we only ever sees one side. Our moon is one of the largest moons in the Solar System relative to the planet it orbits. It is the only object humanity has set foot on so far other than Earth itself, first during the Apollo 11 mission in 1969. It has no atmosphere and its surface is cratered. The Moon was likely formed after a collision of the early Earth with a large object known as Theia billions of years ago.

moons.name: Phobos
moons.paragraph: Phobos is the larger of the two Martian moons, and it orbits very closely to the planet’s surface, slowly approaching it.
moons.namesake: Greek god of fear, son of Ares (Mars)

moons.name: Deimos
moons.paragraph: Deimos is the smaller of the two moons of Mars; it is not even large enough to have a spherical shape.
moons.namesake: Greek god of dread/terror, son of Ares (Mars)

moons.name: Io
moons.paragraph: Io is a Galilean moon of Jupiter, and the densest moon in the Solar System, and the fourth largest. It is home to a lot of geologic and volcanic activity, giving its surface a strange mix of colors and varied topology. Io has high mountains and volcanoes caused by its extreme geology.
moons.namesake: a Greek mythological figure, lover of Zeus (Jupiter)

moons.name: Europa
moons.paragraph: Europa is a Galilean moon of Jupiter with a thin atmosphere and a smooth surface marked with streaks. It likely contains an extremely deep ocean of liquid water beneath its surface which could potentially contain extraterrestrial life. The geologic activity beneath its surface allows the water to be liquid.
moons.namesake: a Greek mythological figure, consort of Zeus (Jupiter)

moons.name: Ganymede
moons.paragraph: Ganymede is a large Galilean moon of Jupiter. It the largest moon in the Solar System, even bigger than Mercury. It is the only moon known to have a magnetic field. Its surface is made of rock; part of it contains lots of impact craters, while other parts have ridges. Ganymede likely has a large supply of internal water.
moons.namesake: a Greek hero, son of Tros

moons.name: Callisto
moons.paragraph: Callisto is a large moon which has an extremely old and heavily cratered surface, and it is the farthest of the Galilean moons from Jupiter. Like the other outer moons, it may contain an ocean of water under its surface.
moons.namesake: a Greek mythological figure, lover of Zeus (Jupiter)

moons.name: Amalthea
moons.paragraph: Amalthea is an inner moon of Jupiter, and it is irregularly shaped. It contains water ice and has large craters on its surface.
moons.namesake: the foster mother of Zeus (Jupiter) from Greek mythology

moons.name: Mimas
moons.paragraph: Mimas is a large moon of Saturn. It has an enormous impact crater, and its surface is littered with others. It is often compared to the Death Star due to its distinctive appearance.
moons.namesake: a Giant in Greek mythology

moons.name: Enceladus
moons.paragraph: Enceladus is a large Saturnian satellite mostly covered in ice. Its surface contains geysers that eject water vapor and hydrogen into space. It has geologic activity and may contain a subsurface ocean.
moons.namesake: a Giant in Greek mythology

moons.name: Tethys
moons.paragraph: Tethys is a large moon of Saturn. It has a very low density, and it is primarily made of water ice.
moons.namesake: one of the Titans of Greek mythology

moons.name: Dione
moons.paragraph: Dione is a large satellite of Saturn. It is made of mostly water ice, and likely has an internal liquid salt water ocean.
moons.namesake: one of the Titans of Greek mythology

moons.name: Rhea
moons.paragraph: Rhea is a large Saturnian moon. It contains mostly water ice and a homogenous interior.
moons.namesake: one of the Titans of Greek mythology, mother of the gods and wife of Kronos (Saturn)

moons.name: Titan
moons.paragraph: Titan is the largest Saturnian moon, and the only known moon in the Solar System to contain a dense atmosphere. It is also the only place in the Solar System other than Earth to contain liquid on its surface.
moons.namesake: Titans of Greek mythology

moons.name: Hyperion
moons.paragraph: Hyperion is a moon of Saturn, and one of the largest irregularly-shaped bodies in the Solar System. It is composed of mostly water ice.

moons.namesake: Titan god of watchfulness

moons.name: Iapetus

moons.namesake: one of the Titans of Greek mythology

moons.name: Phoebe

moons.name: Janus

moons.name: Calypso
moons.paragraph: Calypso is a small irregular moon of Saturn.
moons.discoveredBy: D. Pacsu, P. Seidelmann, W. Baum, D. Currie
moons.namesake: Calypso from Greek mythology

moons.name: Atlas
moons.paragraph: Atlas is a small satellite of Saturn. It orbits very close to Saturn’s A ring.
moons.namesake: Atlas, a Titan from Greek mythology
moons.nameReason: it “holds” Saturn’s rings on its shoulders, as Atlas held up the sky

moons.name: Prometheus
moons.paragraph: Prometheus is a small irregular inner satellite of Saturn.
moons.namesake: a Titan from Greek mythology

moons.name: Pandora
moons.paragraph: Pandora is a small inner moon of Saturn. It has a very chaotic orbit and it is made of mostly ice.
moons.namesake: Pandora from Greek mythology

moons.name: Pan
moons.paragraph: Pan is the innermost known moon of Saturn, orbiting within the A ring. It is known for its shape similar to a walnut.
moons.namesake: Greek god of the wild, shepherds, and flocks

moons.name: Ariel
moons.paragraph: Ariel is a large Uranian moon. It is made of ice and rock, and it has an extreme seasonal cycle due to its orbit.
moons.namesake: a character in Alexander Pope's poem The Rape of the Lock

moons.name: Umbriel
moons.paragraph: Umbriel is a large moon of Uranus. It is made of ice and rock. It has a dark surface and has been cratered.
moons.namesake: a character in Alexander Pope's poem The Rape of the Lock

moons.name: Titania
moons.paragraph: Titania is the largest Uranian moon. Its surface is cratered and relatively dark.
moons.namesake: the queen of the fairies in Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream

moons.name: Oberon
moons.paragraph: Oberon is a large moon that orbits far from Uranus. Its surface is very dark and contains ice, rock, and a surface of craters.
moons.namesake: the king of the fairies in Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream

moons.name: Miranda
moons.paragraph: Miranda is the smallest and innermost major Uranian moon. It has extreme seasonal cycles.
moons.namesake: Miranda from Shakespeare's The Tempest

moons.name: Cordelia
moons.paragraph: Cordelia is the innermost known moon of Uranus.
moons.namesake: the youngest daughter of Lear in Shakespeare's King Lear

moons.name: Ophelia
moons.paragraph: Ophelia is an irregular satellite of Uranus.
moons.namesake: the daughter of Polonius in Shakespeare's Hamlet

moons.name: Triton
moons.paragraph: Triton is the largest moon of Neptune. It orbits retrograde, in the opposite direction of Neptune’s rotation; it is the largest moon in the Solar System that does this. It is likely a captured dwarf planet. Its surface is mostly made of liquid nitrogen and water ice.
moons.namesake: Greek sea god, son of Poseidon (Neptune)

moons.name: Nereid
moons.paragraph: Nereid is a satellite of Neptune. It has the most eccentric orbit of any moon in the Solar System.
moons.namesake: Nereids, sea nymphs that accompany Poseidson (Neptune) in Greek mythology

moons.name: Naiad
moons.paragraph: Naiad is the innermost moon of Neptune. It will eventually crash into Neptune’s surface in the future and become a new ring.
moons.namesake: Naiads of Greek mythology, nymphs that preside over water

moons.name: Thalassa
moons.paragraph: Thalassa is an inner moon of Neptune.
moons.namesake: Greek sea goddess

moons.name: Despina
moons.paragraph: Despina is a small inner moon of Neptune.
moons.namesake: Despoina, a nymph from Greek mythology, and daughter of Poseidon (Neptune)

moons.name: Galatea
moons.paragraph: Galatea is a small inner satellite of Neptune.
moons.namesake: one of the Nereids of Greek mythology

moons.name: Larissa
moons.paragraph: Larissa is a small moon of Neptune.
moons.discoveredBy: H. Reitsema, W. Hubbard, L. Lebofsky, D. Tholen
moons.namesake: a lover of Poseidon (Neptune) in Greek mythology

moons.name: Proteus
moons.paragraph: Proteus is the second largest moon of Neptune. It is mostly made of ice and it has an irregular shape.
moons.namesake: a sea god in Greek mythology

moons.name: Halimede
moons.paragraph: Halimede is a moon of Neptune.

moons.name: Psamathe
moons.paragraph: Psamanthe is a moon of Neptune.

moons.name: Sao
moons.paragraph: Sao is a satellite of Neptune.

moons.name: Laomedeia
moons.paragraph: Laomedeia is a moon of Neptune.

moons.name: Neso
moons.paragraph: Neso is a satellite of Neptune.

moons.name: Hippocamp
moons.paragraph: Hippocamp is a moon of Neptune.

moons.name: Charon
moons.paragraph: Charon is the largest Plutonian moon, and the largest moon among the dwarf planets. It is so large that it is gravitationally locked to Pluto, and the two objects seem to be in a binary system, facing each other at all times.
moons.namesake: the ferryman of Hades (Pluto) in Greek mythology, who carried the deceased to the world of the dead

moons.name: Nix
moons.paragraph: Nix is a small moon of Pluto.
moons.namesake: Greek goddess of the night

moons.name: Hydra
moons.paragraph: Hydra is the outermost moon of Pluto.
moons.namesake: nine-headed underworld serpent from Greek mythology

moons.name: Kerberos
moons.paragraph: Kerberos is a small moon of Pluto.
moons.namesake: Cerberus, the three-headed guard dog of Hades (Pluto) and the underworld

moons.name: Styx
moons.paragraph: Styx is the smallest moon of Pluto.
moons.namesake: the river that forms the boundary between Earth and the underworld in Greek mythology

moons.name: Dysnomia
moons.paragraph: Dysnomia is the only moon of Eris. It is the second largest known moon of the dwarf planets.
moons.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
moons.namesake: Greek deity of lawlessness, daughter of Eris

moons.name: Hi’iaka
moons.paragraph: Hi’iaka is a small moon orbiting Haumea, along with Namaka.
moons.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
moons.namesake: Hawaiian goddess of the big island

moons.name: Namaka
moons.paragraph: Namaka is a small moon orbiting Haumea, along with Hi’iaka.
moons.discoveredBy: Michael E. Brown, Chad Trujillo, David Rabinowitz
moons.namesake: Hawaiian goddess of the sea

moons.name: S/2015 (136472) 1
moons.paragraph: S/2015 (136472) 1 is the sole moon of Makemake.
moons.discoveredBy: A. Parker, M. Buie, W. Grundy, K. Noll

other.name: Pallas
other.paragraph: Pallas is the third largest asteroid in the Solar System. It is composed of minerals.

other.name: Vesta
other.paragraph: Vesta is the second largest known asteroid. It is the brightest asteroid visible from Earth.
other.namesake: Roman goddess of home and hearth

other.name: Lutetia
other.paragraph: The Rosetta Spacecraft flew by Lutetia in 2010.

other.name: Eugenia
other.paragraph: Eugenia is believed to have a small satellite.

other.name: Kleopatra
other.paragraph: Kleopatra is shaped like a dog bone.

other.name: Ida
other.paragraph: Ida was imaged by the Galileo mission in 1993. It has a small satellite named Dactyl.

other.name: Mathilde
other.paragraph: The NEAR mission studied Mathilde in 1997.

other.name: Eros
other.paragraph: Eros was imaged by the Galileo mission in 1991.

other.name: Apollo
other.paragraph: Apollo was the first discovered Earth-crossing asteroid.

other.name: Chiron
other.paragraph: Chiron is both an asteroid and a comet near Saturn and Uranus. It is in a wild and chaotic orbit.

other.name: Steins
other.paragraph: Steins was studied by the Rosetta spacecraft in 2008.

other.name: Toutatis
other.paragraph: Toutatis is a double object, made of two objects that collided.

other.name: AnneFrank
other.paragraph: AnneFrank was the target of a flyby by the Stardust spacecraft in 2002.

other.name: Braille
other.paragraph: Braille was the target of a flyby by the Deep Space 1 spacecraft in 1999.

other.name: Itokawa
other.paragraph: Itokawa is a near-Earth target asteroid sampled by the Hayabusa spacecraft in 2005.

other.name: Bennu
other.paragraph: Bennu is a near-Earth asteroid sampled by the OSIRIS-REx spacecraft in 2018.

other.name: Halley
other.paragraph: Halley’s Comet is a short-period comet which is visible every 75-76 years from Earth. It last appeared in 1986, and will appear again in 2061. It is composed of ice and dust.
